properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A weather system has stalled near Edmonton, and is giving heavy snow. 5-8 cm has fallen in a line from Leduc to Barrhead, and another 5 cm is expected by this afternoon. The band of snow will move slowly eastwards this afternoon, giving totals close to 10 cm. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, is expected. An intense frontal system is rapidly approaching the south coast this morning. Moderate rainfall will begin over west Vancouver Island late this morning. This evening the rain will intensify significantly before it eases off late Thursday morning. Total rainfall accumulations of 100 mm are expected except up to 120 mm near Zeballos and Tahsis. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills continues. The coldest wind chill values will be near minus 55. Temperatures near minus 40 with light winds are creating wind chill values near minus 55 this morning. Temperatures will moderate slightly this afternoon, but wind chills may approach minus 55 again tonight. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, is expected. An intense frontal system is rapidly approaching the south coast today. Moderate rain will start near mid day and become heavy at times overnight tonight. East Vancouver Island near Bowser is expected to get 80 to 100 mm of rain before it eases Thursday morning. Howe Sound, the North Shore, and the northeast and central Metro Vancouver regions are expected to receive up to 80 mm of rain from this storm. Heavy rain is expected to ease by mid day Thursday. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible.
